1
00:00:03,017 --> 00:00:30,088
namo tassa bhagavato arahato samma sambuddhassa namo tassa bhagavato arahato samma sambuddhassa namo tassa bhagavato arahato samma sambuddhassa

2
00:00:30,068 --> 00:00:34,718
homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble and fully self-enlightened one.

3
00:00:46,582 --> 00:00:49,308
So I thought I'd give a little talk around faith.

4
00:00:51,667 --> 00:00:56,738
which in the Buddha's understanding is fundamental.

5
00:00:57,179 --> 00:00:59,384
Nothing happens without faith.

6
00:01:00,987 --> 00:01:06,740
And I read a rather nice little essay on it by Jnana Ponica, whom some of you might know.

7
00:01:06,721 --> 00:01:12,367
a very famous German monk who started the Buddhist Publication Society up in Kandy.

8
00:01:13,228 --> 00:01:17,334
Didn't write all that much himself, but what he wrote was influential.

9
00:01:18,174 --> 00:01:25,823
And his main book, The Heart of Buddhist Meditation, still remains a classic really on meditation.

10
00:01:25,843 --> 00:01:33,132
The Heart of Buddhist Meditation.

11
00:01:34,665 --> 00:01:40,438
The way I would like to tackle it is from these three constituents of an act of consciousness.

12
00:01:40,718 --> 00:01:44,647
I'm getting this from the Abhidhamma, but actually it should be pretty obvious to us.

13
00:01:45,370 --> 00:01:53,787
Not being too specific about one act of consciousness, but in a series, shall we say, of consciousnesses.

14
00:01:53,768 --> 00:01:58,478
You always have the intellectual part, the cognitive part, the understanding.

15
00:01:59,421 --> 00:02:05,715
There's always some affective part, your emotional involvement.

16
00:02:06,798 --> 00:02:12,671
And for an action, there has to be what's known as a cognitive, there has to be an act of will.

17
00:02:12,651 --> 00:02:19,125
And you will notice that in my explanation there, I use my hand to point to three centers.

18
00:02:19,665 --> 00:02:32,532
So they're your basic chakras, the one in the middle of your head signifying your understanding, the heart in the middle of your chest, and the one in your belly.

19
00:02:32,513 --> 00:02:43,194
And it's interesting that, just a little aside, that if you look at the way Buddhism grew, it was very much a cognitive effort.

20
00:02:43,254 --> 00:02:50,370
The Buddha's teaching is very much about, first of all, understanding and everything takes place, everything flows.

21
00:02:50,349 --> 00:03:04,127
but that became too rigid, too dry perhaps, so that the next wave through Mahayana was raising up karuna, raising up the heart to the level of pañña, wisdom.

22
00:03:04,807 --> 00:03:07,150
So karuna and pañña became equal, you see.

23
00:03:07,790 --> 00:03:15,800
And if you go over to the Far East, to Japan, their center is very much in the hara, you know, the will.

24
00:03:18,447 --> 00:03:19,108
a samurai.

25
00:03:20,909 --> 00:03:22,092
Just a little aside, you understand.

26
00:03:22,211 --> 00:03:23,013
Nothing to do with faith.

27
00:03:26,198 --> 00:03:32,806
So these three things I want to just look at from the point of view of faith.

28
00:03:34,088 --> 00:03:39,417
And before we do that, I have to make one big distinction between faith and belief.

29
00:03:40,718 --> 00:03:45,264
So a belief is faith in a statement.

30
00:03:45,650 --> 00:03:54,539
So if you say, there is no God, or there is a God, then that's a statement which, in effect, you can't prove either one way or the other.

31
00:03:55,139 --> 00:04:01,747
But if you believe it, then it would come under a belief rather than faith.

32
00:04:01,986 --> 00:04:11,818
So when we're talking about faith this evening, it's concerned with an attitude, trust, confidence.

33
00:04:11,837 --> 00:04:14,661
That's what we're talking about.

34
00:04:14,640 --> 00:04:22,658
To give us some idea as to what we mean by that, we can take a few ordinary things that we do which demand faith.

35
00:04:24,101 --> 00:04:30,776
If you take, for instance, supposing now you decided to climb Everest, you see.

36
00:04:35,987 --> 00:04:39,213
So there would have to be these three things, wouldn't there?

37
00:04:39,233 --> 00:04:47,464
You'd have to have understood what the actual path of Everest means and what it might take.

38
00:04:47,865 --> 00:04:49,288
It has to be that understanding.

39
00:04:50,228 --> 00:04:53,254
There has to be the desire to get up there, doesn't there?

40
00:04:53,369 --> 00:05:22,177
you might read about it and think that's very interesting but there's no desire to go up to go up Everest and you might of course have a good understanding as to what it's going to take you might have an incredible desire but somehow you just can't get your boots on and that's that's the lack of will you see that's the lack of will

41
00:05:23,271 --> 00:05:28,100
Lots of times like that in our lives, isn't there?

42
00:05:28,120 --> 00:05:42,983
So somebody came and she was in quite an upset state because she was convinced that she had throat cancer, this particular person.

43
00:05:43,002 --> 00:05:47,170
And she had no trust in her doctors.

44
00:05:47,841 --> 00:05:53,771
So she wouldn't even go for a, what do they call it, an autopsy?

45
00:05:53,831 --> 00:05:54,973
Is it autopsy?

46
00:05:55,675 --> 00:05:56,956
Biopsy, not an autopsy.

47
00:05:56,976 --> 00:05:58,680
She wasn't dead yet.

48
00:05:59,380 --> 00:06:00,262
She hadn't got there yet.

49
00:06:00,281 --> 00:06:08,735
A little biopsy on the grounds that she didn't trust the doctors.

50
00:06:08,817 --> 00:06:33,541
And as we were discussing it and seeing what other options were open, it finally of course began to show that what was really undermining her faith wasn't at all to do with the doctors or the profession, it was the fear that in fact she may have throat cancer.

51
00:06:33,521 --> 00:06:39,374
So that underlying fear was as it were translated into a lack of faith.

52
00:06:41,939 --> 00:06:44,144
I think in this case she actually did eventually go.

53
00:06:44,184 --> 00:06:53,201
But if you think of anything you have to do with doctors, you have to have a primary faith that their diagnosis is correct.

54
00:06:54,785 --> 00:06:59,052
and that the medicine they prescribe is correct.

55
00:06:59,833 --> 00:07:05,401
Now in the old days you would have just had blind faith, the doctor.

56
00:07:06,562 --> 00:07:09,187
My parents wouldn't have ever argued with a doctor.

57
00:07:09,807 --> 00:07:16,338
If the doctor said this pimple on your nose is a dreadful cancer they would have believed it.

58
00:07:16,999 --> 00:07:20,403
It wouldn't have occurred to them to question the diagnosis.

59
00:07:20,384 --> 00:07:25,250
These days we're a bit more argumentative.

60
00:07:27,314 --> 00:07:30,899
And you want to know why and what happens.

61
00:07:33,122 --> 00:07:39,831
Recently I went in to the doctor with a tinnitus which had just arrived out of nowhere.

62
00:07:40,632 --> 00:07:42,696
And she said, I'll send you for a blood test.

63
00:07:42,716 --> 00:07:43,737
I said, a blood test?

64
00:07:45,761 --> 00:07:49,446
I had to squeeze out of her why she was sending me for a blood test.

65
00:07:50,692 --> 00:07:51,293
I won't tell you.

66
00:07:55,584 --> 00:08:04,649
So this whole business of even taking medicine, even going for an operation, you've got to have that trust in the surgeon.

67
00:08:06,605 --> 00:08:09,108
You take another thing that we do in our lives, a job.

68
00:08:09,149 --> 00:08:18,485
So if you're taking on a job, especially a job which you know will stretch you, then there has to be these three elements.

69
00:08:18,504 --> 00:08:23,533
There has to be, first of all, that you've understood what the job is asking you to do.

70
00:08:23,512 --> 00:08:27,540
There has to be that attraction to the job, there has to be a desire to do it.

71
00:08:28,502 --> 00:08:33,971
And then, you know, finally you've got to sign on the dotted line, or else it just doesn't happen.

72
00:08:34,212 --> 00:08:37,238
And that's the act, that's the commitment, the act of will.

73
00:08:38,419 --> 00:08:45,994
And there, sometimes what stops us is that doubt, can I do it, can I do it, you see.

74
00:08:45,974 --> 00:08:48,909
So you can see that the opposite of faith is doubt.

75
00:08:49,392 --> 00:08:53,654
There's something that stops you from that commitment.

76
00:08:55,897 --> 00:09:01,868
And if we take another one, it's forming a relationship or getting married.

77
00:09:02,509 --> 00:09:09,903
This takes us into the realm of a more intimate human relationship where actually your trust is in this other person.

78
00:09:10,024 --> 00:09:14,732
They're not going to abuse you or take advantage of you.

79
00:09:15,815 --> 00:09:16,976
Take all your money.

80
00:09:18,239 --> 00:09:21,683
There's got to be that trust.

81
00:09:22,065 --> 00:09:31,479
And again, there is that knowledge that comes of knowing the other person long enough, the confidence that arises with that.

82
00:09:31,720 --> 00:09:36,447
Then, of course, that special love that one has with that sort of relationship.

83
00:09:37,268 --> 00:09:42,897
And then, eventually, there's got to be that movement towards yes, yes.

84
00:09:45,003 --> 00:09:51,592
So these things are just little examples which we now translate into the spiritual life.

85
00:09:52,293 --> 00:10:01,167
So when it comes to the spiritual life, and specifically around Buddhism, faith, the Buddha calls the spiritual faculty.

86
00:10:01,927 --> 00:10:05,913
Interestingly enough, he doesn't put it in with the factors of enlightenment.

87
00:10:07,447 --> 00:10:20,190
And the presumption is, at least I presume, is that by the time you're actually meditating, the faith must be there, at least some level of faith.

88
00:10:21,368 --> 00:10:34,764
Because the facts of enlightenment are put into the Satipatthana discourse, the discourse on how to establish mindfulness or this awareness which leads us to the awakening.

89
00:10:35,926 --> 00:10:38,308
But the five faculties are not there.

90
00:10:38,349 --> 00:10:41,511
They're talked about in other places.

91
00:10:42,052 --> 00:10:45,317
What's in that particular scripture are the seven factors of enlightenment.

92
00:10:46,866 --> 00:10:52,678
So when it comes to the faculty, it seems to me, faith seems to me presumed.

93
00:10:53,600 --> 00:11:04,942
So all of you here now, you see, whatever commitment you have towards the Buddha's teaching, the fact is you wouldn't be here were it not that there was some faith.

94
00:11:06,322 --> 00:11:19,639
And if we now go back to what faith entails, the cognitive part, the actual part of understanding, so that's pointed out as three different stages.

95
00:11:20,019 --> 00:11:28,671
The first one is you hear the doctrine, you hear the teaching, and that immediately, as it were, arouses interest.

96
00:11:28,691 --> 00:11:33,758
There's also something that's stirring in the heart, that this is the truth, an attraction.

97
00:11:33,778 --> 00:11:35,740
There must be some sort of an attraction.

98
00:11:37,626 --> 00:11:43,756
And then after you've heard it and you read about it, there are, shall we say, reflections about it.

99
00:11:43,917 --> 00:11:52,951
So that the knowledge which was given, hearsay, read, now becomes your own personal understanding by way of your own reflections.

100
00:11:53,422 --> 00:12:05,856
And the more that happens, the more confidence arises, the more faith happens, the more faith arises in us about the doctrine, because now in a sense it's becoming our way of thinking, our way of understanding.

101
00:12:06,177 --> 00:12:07,759
So it's my way, not the Buddha's way.

102
00:12:08,340 --> 00:12:10,423
I'm slowly turning towards that.

103
00:12:13,966 --> 00:12:21,336
But there's still that missing link between an understanding which is intellectual and the actual experience.

104
00:12:21,940 --> 00:12:29,722
So it's all right saying that everything arises and passes away, and I mean, there are very few people in the world who wouldn't grasp that.

105
00:12:30,596 --> 00:12:37,971
And when we turn inward and we just look around a little bit, we can see that thoughts arise and pass away, emotions arise and pass away, feelings arise.

106
00:12:38,331 --> 00:12:52,538
I mean, it's not a brain twister to actually go into that, but it's actually coming to the point where this I, this me, which feels so solid, is also arising and passing away.

107
00:12:52,518 --> 00:13:08,020
So turning inward and really coming to terms with what transience actually means at a deeper level through our meditation, that now becomes, shall we say, a knowledge which is also carrying into experience.

108
00:13:08,701 --> 00:13:16,312
But we would never have got there, really, without that initial confidence.

109
00:13:16,332 --> 00:13:17,715
See, that initial confidence.

110
00:13:21,644 --> 00:13:36,686
When it comes to the heart itself, there's that feeling of trust which comes in, to trust somebody, to have confidence in, faith in somebody.

111
00:13:37,927 --> 00:13:41,273
And then there's a desire to devote oneself.

112
00:13:43,024 --> 00:13:50,517
sort of a loyal service to the Dharma, for as much as it feeds you personally.

113
00:13:51,177 --> 00:14:01,634
So if you're devoted to somebody, then you're there to actually help, please, make them happy.

114
00:14:03,256 --> 00:14:06,282
A mother and father devoted to their children.

115
00:14:08,320 --> 00:14:13,807
So that act of devotion is not just a sort of lovey-dovey thing.

116
00:14:14,047 --> 00:14:18,732
It's part of that movement of the heart to give of oneself.

117
00:14:19,813 --> 00:14:20,995
A votary offering.

118
00:14:21,556 --> 00:14:22,256
It's an offering.

119
00:14:24,440 --> 00:14:34,972
And running along with that, there's love, which translates as a sort of lightness, a sort of joy in faith.

120
00:14:37,817 --> 00:14:37,937
Yeah?

121
00:14:37,956 --> 00:14:38,057
Yeah?

122
00:14:39,302 --> 00:14:46,130
And then once those two are there, there comes this point of a commitment.

123
00:14:46,770 --> 00:14:51,096
And the commitment is at all different levels.

124
00:14:51,996 --> 00:14:54,900
So it might be just the commitment to practice a bit of meditation.

125
00:14:55,922 --> 00:15:02,369
And eventually it's a commitment to actually follow the Buddha's path as your center line.

126
00:15:03,710 --> 00:15:06,052
And a total life's devotion to it.

127
00:15:07,534 --> 00:15:15,970
So, for instance, when people take refuges, refuges and precepts, I mean, that's the normal way in all forms of Buddhism.

128
00:15:15,990 --> 00:15:20,298
So the refuges are the Buddha, the Dharma, and the Sangha.

129
00:15:20,317 --> 00:15:25,947
And then you take the five precepts, which is just your basic morality, not to kill anybody, steal, etc.,

130
00:15:27,159 --> 00:15:34,966
But the first part, the taking of refuge in the Buddha Dhamma Sangha, is an act of commitment dependent on the person.

131
00:15:35,326 --> 00:15:50,178
So it might be that they are committed to it, just on a level of, a rather superficial level of, you know, that the Buddha's teaching is good, and it's part of my spiritual smorgasbord, you know.

132
00:15:50,460 --> 00:15:54,863
I've got all this other stuff, and here's the Buddha's teaching over here, and I do a bit of that.

133
00:15:56,124 --> 00:15:56,745
That's fine.

134
00:15:57,788 --> 00:16:11,548
As the teaching takes a more central position in your life, then of course the commitment comes for more, to give oneself more to that teaching.

135
00:16:12,769 --> 00:16:15,914
But there still might be a holding back, you see.

136
00:16:15,894 --> 00:16:22,085
So it takes a long time to actually commit yourself to something, especially if you are converted to it.

137
00:16:22,546 --> 00:16:39,152
If you're born into a religion, if you're born into a spiritual way of life, then it's just natural to you because ever since you woke up, you've been sort of cajoled to make that sort of devotion, to make that sort of act of devotion.

138
00:16:39,131 --> 00:16:56,600
But for those who have come from other forms and come into Buddhism, then it takes quite a long time before you ever get to that point of actually, if ever of course, that you actually commit yourself in terms of this life.

139
00:16:57,576 --> 00:17:03,125
Now, you only get back what you give.

140
00:17:03,988 --> 00:17:08,194
So if you give a bit of commitment, then you get a little bit back.

141
00:17:09,797 --> 00:17:12,382
If you give a bit more, you get a bit more back.

142
00:17:12,402 --> 00:17:16,327
And if you give the whole thing, then eventually you get the whole thing.

143
00:17:16,307 --> 00:17:16,647
That.

144
00:17:16,969 --> 00:17:17,388
You see what I mean?

145
00:17:17,429 --> 00:17:17,990
It's like, yeah?

146
00:17:18,490 --> 00:17:23,416
It's like in a relationship, if you say, well, I love you a bit, and the other person says, well, I love you a bit.

147
00:17:23,737 --> 00:17:24,156
See?

148
00:17:25,018 --> 00:17:33,769
And it slowly builds up until finally there's some sort of connection, which one can call a marriage in one form or another.

149
00:17:33,808 --> 00:17:34,490
You see?

150
00:17:35,090 --> 00:17:38,755
So that's the same with our relationship to the spiritual path.

151
00:17:38,734 --> 00:17:46,290
And that commitment can't be forced, you can't say, oh well, I'm fed up with messing around now, I'm going to devote myself to the Buddha Dhamma Sangha.

152
00:17:46,351 --> 00:17:50,220
Not at all, because it's a movement within the heart, right?

153
00:17:50,240 --> 00:17:58,396
And there just comes a time in a person's life when they make these little commitments, so it grows, it grows, it grows.

154
00:17:59,743 --> 00:18:09,659
Now when that happens, you see, or as that happens, then one gets the satisfaction of acts of commitment based on faith.

155
00:18:10,619 --> 00:18:13,403
So here's one way of putting it.

156
00:18:13,464 --> 00:18:22,478
This is taken from the commentary, but it also turns up in what's known as the Questions of King Melinda, which was written quite a while after the Buddha.

157
00:18:23,977 --> 00:18:32,821
And it says, as a water purifying gem of the universal monarch, he has seven of these by the way,

158
00:18:33,460 --> 00:18:44,457
As a water purifying gem of the universal monarch thrown into water causes solids, alluvia, water weeds and mud to subside and makes the water clear, transparent and undisturbed.

159
00:18:45,178 --> 00:18:54,472
So faith arising discards the hindrances, causes the corruptions to subside, purifies the mind and makes it undisturbed.

160
00:18:54,452 --> 00:19:04,279
the mind being purified, and the aspirant of the noble family gives gifts, observes the precepts, performs the duties of the Apostle and commences Bhavana.

161
00:19:04,840 --> 00:19:09,795
Thus, faith should be known to have purifying as its characteristic.

162
00:19:11,007 --> 00:19:27,731
So these performs the duties of the Uposatha is in Buddhist countries, you know, these full moon and the new moon and the quarters are times when lay people go to the monastery and make a special day of it, especially the full moon.

163
00:19:27,751 --> 00:19:30,957
And commencing Bhavana, Bhavana is meditation.

164
00:19:30,936 --> 00:19:32,481
Bhāvan is meditation.

165
00:19:32,501 --> 00:19:38,681
So here we have the purifying of water, transparency.

166
00:19:38,740 --> 00:19:44,659
Now all you've got to think about is those times when your life has been full of doubt

167
00:19:44,825 --> 00:19:52,055
Either should you move house, should you go for this job or that job, should you go into this relationship or that relationship.

168
00:19:52,075 --> 00:20:03,809
In those times of doubt, you see, as soon as there's a commitment, as soon as there's a decision and a commitment, all the stuff around that disappears, doesn't it?

169
00:20:06,094 --> 00:20:12,402
All that disturbance, all the doubt, all the fear, it just clarifies, it just disappears.

170
00:20:13,224 --> 00:20:33,554
So that's what this is pointing to, that an act of faith is, or an act of taking refuge in Buddhist language, to take the refuge in, a refuge, is that point where all doubts, finally, about how one should lead one's spiritual life begin to fade away.

171
00:20:34,915 --> 00:20:36,538
And one is clear, one is clear.

172
00:20:36,858 --> 00:20:42,507
So that's its effect on us.

173
00:20:48,982 --> 00:21:13,067
talking again just a little bit about the intellect and the affective the emotional thing if something is only intellective if it's only an understanding coming from the mind and it doesn't have the force of the heart behind it then it remains brittle it remains quite brittle and it can easily be cracked by another argument

174
00:21:13,047 --> 00:21:41,788
somebody coming along like for instance later on there's a question on rebirth you see so if a person thinks well you have to believe in rebirth to be a Buddhist and I can't really believe that then the whole thing shatters so if faith is only at that sort of intellectual understanding that this is ok I understand it and all that but it doesn't without the heart behind it it's not going to really penetrate it's not really going to have the effect of true devotion

175
00:21:42,932 --> 00:21:56,890
If on the other hand it's only the heart, so sometimes one is drawn, a type of person might be drawn simply by seeing, seeing a statue of the Buddha.

176
00:21:57,029 --> 00:22:00,434
I know people as soon as they've seen a statue of Buddha they sort of fall in love with it.

177
00:22:00,934 --> 00:22:06,342
Something in their memory has clicked and there's this heart connection.

178
00:22:06,321 --> 00:22:07,866
And there's that leap of faith.

179
00:22:08,548 --> 00:22:17,074
But if that's not balanced with, of course, some sort of intellectual understanding about what they're doing, then we would call that blind faith.

180
00:22:17,542 --> 00:22:45,828
and what happens then is an easy falling into belief systems so I believe the Buddha is right whatever the Buddha says it's got to be right and what that does to the practitioner is it undermines their commitment to practice I mean if you have a belief that oh yeah the Buddha is right then why prove it see the whole point of the practice that we do the Bhāvanā, the Vipassanā is that question

181
00:22:45,808 --> 00:22:47,752
Is the Buddha correct?

182
00:22:48,013 --> 00:22:48,775
Has he got it right?

183
00:22:49,938 --> 00:22:53,325
I mean, you're not saying that to yourself when you sit, I hope.

184
00:22:53,345 --> 00:22:56,813
But that's the underlying basis of the great doubt.

185
00:22:56,853 --> 00:22:59,459
This is not doubt as a skeptical thing.

186
00:22:59,960 --> 00:23:02,184
This is not coming from fear.

187
00:23:02,546 --> 00:23:05,471
It's coming from a desire to really know

188
00:23:05,451 --> 00:23:11,401
personally, as a personal experience, whether the Buddha's liberation is true.

189
00:23:12,020 --> 00:23:16,548
And whether once one gets to this point of nibbana, whether there isn't in fact more.

190
00:23:17,730 --> 00:23:20,554
We might get there and we think, no, this isn't it.

191
00:23:21,755 --> 00:23:22,656
I've got to keep going.

192
00:23:23,337 --> 00:23:23,979
You don't know, do you?

193
00:23:24,759 --> 00:23:33,972
And it's that sort of doubt which is better translated as a wonder, a philosopher's wonder, which drives our meditation.

194
00:23:33,952 --> 00:23:38,939
So in your meditation, if you're just sitting there watching, looking, you see, that won't do.

195
00:23:38,959 --> 00:23:40,320
It won't do, you see.

196
00:23:40,401 --> 00:23:41,623
That's called being lazy.

197
00:23:42,262 --> 00:23:45,067
There has to also be that sense of curiosity.

198
00:23:45,667 --> 00:23:53,657
If the curiosity is not there, just that simple question mark in the mind, a way of looking, then insight can't arise.

199
00:23:54,178 --> 00:23:55,339
So the Buddha is quite clear.

200
00:23:55,380 --> 00:23:57,041
Awareness.

201
00:23:57,173 --> 00:24:02,226
Without awareness, without placing that attention on something, insight can't arise.

202
00:24:03,328 --> 00:24:05,253
So you can't have insight without the awareness.

203
00:24:05,273 --> 00:24:13,596
But on the other hand, that insight won't arise unless there is that curiosity in the mind, that wanting to know.

204
00:24:15,701 --> 00:24:45,709
so those two are you have to have them in balance and of course when you say balance there's not some objective balance you can't go on a weighing scale and say well I've got a bit of this and I've got a bit of that it's to do with the individual so that every individual has to have that balance within themselves of an intellectual understanding and a commitment in terms of their devotion in terms of what their heart wants to do

205
00:24:45,689 --> 00:24:56,579
And that will, you know, it's just like we were saying about not getting your boots on.

206
00:24:56,720 --> 00:25:00,544
So there can be always this lovely intellectual understanding.

207
00:25:00,564 --> 00:25:07,250
Some people read so much and they can splurge it all out, you know, and quote ad infinitum.

208
00:25:07,811 --> 00:25:12,777
And sometimes they've got a good feeling behind it, but they don't practice.

209
00:25:13,988 --> 00:25:14,750
No practice at all.

210
00:25:15,511 --> 00:25:16,394
Don't do any meditation.

211
00:25:17,679 --> 00:25:19,443
See, now what stops them doing that?

212
00:25:19,483 --> 00:25:24,218
What stops them making that little effort to actually climb the mountain?

213
00:25:24,535 --> 00:25:27,838
And that's the lack of will, you see, the lack of commitment.

214
00:25:27,859 --> 00:25:32,905
So unless there's that too, there can't be progress on the path.

215
00:25:34,428 --> 00:25:45,143
And it's interesting that the Buddha puts faith opposite, or he balances faith in the five faculties, he balances it with insight.

216
00:25:46,877 --> 00:25:53,616
So if there's no faith, if there's not that act of devotion to the practice, then insight can't come up.

217
00:25:54,198 --> 00:25:57,748
So these two things are intimately linked.

218
00:26:02,707 --> 00:26:22,404
And eventually when we have an insight which is an insight into the final goal, which is known as entering the stream, the Sotapanna, at that point this faith becomes unshakable.

219
00:26:22,644 --> 00:26:30,132
It's then known not so much as an indriya, which we translate as faculty, it becomes a bala, which means a strength.

220
00:26:30,112 --> 00:26:38,070
So now that faith now is unshakable because that person has actually seen the top of the mountain.

221
00:26:38,271 --> 00:26:39,173
They know where it is.

222
00:26:39,193 --> 00:26:40,897
It's no longer clouded.

223
00:26:41,299 --> 00:26:43,962
It's not that they can't see it because they've actually touched it.

224
00:26:45,344 --> 00:26:54,472
And now that faith, which is a strength, of course, must necessarily draw them to the end of the path through the next few stages.

225
00:26:54,492 --> 00:27:04,182
So until, you see, it's understood that until we have intuited this nirvanic moment, faith will always have a little shake in it.

226
00:27:04,423 --> 00:27:06,565
There'll always be a little shake in it.

227
00:27:06,545 --> 00:27:13,550
And that really brings us to what undermines our faith, what undermines your commitment to the practice.

228
00:27:20,382 --> 00:27:24,787
The first one we've already talked about, this confusion between faith and belief.

229
00:27:26,048 --> 00:27:31,594
So you can very easily slip into that lazy place where you say, well, I believe the Buddha, you know, what's the point?

230
00:27:31,874 --> 00:27:33,875
And it undermines that practice.

231
00:27:33,895 --> 00:27:37,799
So you've got to keep up that sense of curiosity, that sense of wanting to know.

232
00:27:38,760 --> 00:27:44,207
And, you know, the Buddha sort of laid that out very clearly when he visited the Kalamas.

233
00:27:44,247 --> 00:27:45,468
It's a very famous discourse.

234
00:27:45,488 --> 00:27:48,971
Everybody quotes it, so I may as well quote it myself.

235
00:27:49,508 --> 00:27:56,335
So he ended up at the village of the Kalamas, and the Kalamas said to him, we're in a state of calamity.

236
00:27:56,634 --> 00:28:05,884
And he said, everybody who comes here tells us that this is what it's all about, this is the truth, and everybody else is wrong.

237
00:28:06,605 --> 00:28:09,346
So, you know, who are we to believe?

238
00:28:09,407 --> 00:28:11,569
Where are we to go, you see?

239
00:28:11,589 --> 00:28:14,992
And he says, do not believe anything simply because you've heard it,

240
00:28:16,778 --> 00:28:20,663
Simply because it is tradition handed down for many generations.

241
00:28:22,445 --> 00:28:25,329
Simply because it is spoken and rumoured by the many.

242
00:28:27,352 --> 00:28:30,296
Simply because it is found written in your religious books.

243
00:28:31,837 --> 00:28:34,682
And simply on the authority of your teachers and elders.

244
00:28:35,943 --> 00:28:37,385
In other words, don't believe anything.

245
00:28:38,480 --> 00:28:48,640
And then he says, only when it works for you, only when you've tried it out, only when it's something which is of benefit to you, would you then commit yourself to it.

246
00:28:52,145 --> 00:29:00,301
So belief is something which would be contrary to the Buddha's path as such.

247
00:29:04,805 --> 00:29:11,551
The other thing is that we talked about was this balance between devotion or the heart and the understanding.

248
00:29:13,134 --> 00:29:14,715
And this is from the commentaries.

249
00:29:14,976 --> 00:29:22,845
And it says, for one strong in faith and weak in understanding has confidence uncritically and groundlessly.

250
00:29:23,404 --> 00:29:24,507
So that's your blind faith.

251
00:29:24,527 --> 00:29:25,488
That's your gullibility.

252
00:29:25,788 --> 00:29:27,690
That's believing something, right?

253
00:29:29,105 --> 00:29:40,118
For one strong in understanding and weak in faith errs on the side of cunning and is as hard to cure as one sick of a disease caused by medicine.

254
00:29:41,099 --> 00:29:42,321
Interesting, isn't it?

255
00:29:42,741 --> 00:29:44,765
We know about the side effects of drugs.

256
00:29:46,205 --> 00:29:49,410
One strong in understanding and weak in faith.

257
00:29:50,050 --> 00:29:50,392
You see?

258
00:29:51,133 --> 00:29:54,656
So what they're saying here, what he's saying here is that...

259
00:29:55,143 --> 00:30:08,521
you can have such a good intellectual grasp of Buddhism that you actually believe you've experienced it.

260
00:30:10,805 --> 00:30:18,635
And there's a total confusion between something that has been so clearly understood and something which has been directly experienced.

261
00:30:20,201 --> 00:30:25,888
And I knew of a monk who actually believed that himself.

262
00:30:26,509 --> 00:30:31,957
He did, he had an enormous, wonderful, deep grasp of the Dharma.

263
00:30:31,977 --> 00:30:37,284
And he was convinced that he must be a reborn stream entrant.

264
00:30:37,304 --> 00:30:44,854
In other words, he was already, he'd already somewhere in his past life, I mean he had to believe that, he had intuited Nibbana.

265
00:30:44,874 --> 00:30:49,720
Or else how could he have this amazing, wonderful understanding of the Buddha's teaching?

266
00:30:49,700 --> 00:30:58,848
And that is such an easy confusion, related to those who have a very strong intellect.

267
00:31:11,738 --> 00:31:17,984
And so it then goes on to say, with the balancing of the two, a person has confidence where there are grounds for it.

268
00:31:18,424 --> 00:31:20,807
In other words, it's the balance that we're looking for.

269
00:31:24,951 --> 00:31:31,538
The other one is more to do with self-expectation.

270
00:31:31,598 --> 00:31:34,142
The big one about self-doubt.

271
00:31:34,502 --> 00:31:35,683
Everybody can do it but not me.

272
00:31:36,444 --> 00:31:37,746
That sort of thing.

273
00:31:38,182 --> 00:31:43,554
And that can be a real barrier to progress.

274
00:31:44,336 --> 00:31:53,777
There's a particular monk in the scriptures who becomes despairing of his practice and commits suicide.

275
00:31:55,141 --> 00:32:01,868
Fortunately, when the Buddha comes along and is asked, well, what happened to this monk?

276
00:32:02,170 --> 00:32:02,871
Where's he gone?

277
00:32:02,891 --> 00:32:07,817
He says, oh, he became enlightened in the process of committing suicide.

278
00:32:07,836 --> 00:32:09,778
Now, I'm not suggesting, of course, that.

279
00:32:12,823 --> 00:32:14,545
In this case, it was a happy outcome.

280
00:32:15,385 --> 00:32:17,689
But

281
00:32:22,833 --> 00:32:26,109
I don't think there's a deeper despair than spiritual despair.

282
00:32:29,009 --> 00:32:38,962
to despair of somebody, to despair of your ability to have a relationship, to despair of your ability to earn money and live a good life.

283
00:32:40,384 --> 00:32:44,351
All these things that throw people into suicide and jump off bridges.

284
00:32:45,112 --> 00:32:58,070
I'm thinking particularly of a young man in Australia who made, and remember this is a piece of news, who made an enormous amount of wealth on property.

285
00:32:58,050 --> 00:33:04,679
And when that thing crashed in the mid-90s, he committed suicide.

286
00:33:04,699 --> 00:33:12,387
But when we're talking about spiritual despair, that digs at the deepest level of our being, doesn't it?

287
00:33:13,028 --> 00:33:15,030
Because that's what the spiritual life is about.

288
00:33:15,070 --> 00:33:15,811
It's about being.

289
00:33:15,872 --> 00:33:21,038
It's about who are we at fundament.

290
00:33:21,018 --> 00:33:37,138
And to have entered the spiritual path and to have seen the possibility of spiritual advancement and spiritual attainment and that end of suffering and then to despair that one could ever achieve that.

291
00:33:38,279 --> 00:33:41,364
I don't think that's an existential despair.

292
00:33:41,384 --> 00:33:47,752
I don't think you can get worse than that when it comes to despair anyway.

293
00:33:47,772 --> 00:33:48,814
So don't despair.

294
00:33:56,454 --> 00:34:04,598
So that when self-doubt comes up like that, it can often be caused by an over-expectation.

295
00:34:05,160 --> 00:34:09,132
You know, you thought you'd be further along the path than this, than you are now.

296
00:34:09,802 --> 00:34:13,666
And there's pride involved in that and a loss of self-esteem, you know.

297
00:34:14,847 --> 00:34:34,389
I met a man and he said to me, when he first came to meditation, he went to a course, this was back in the 70s, he went to a course of meditation and he went to it as you would go to any old course of calligraphy or basket making or, you know, French or something.

298
00:34:34,949 --> 00:34:39,574
And he went along and the idea was you got an Ibana, you got a certificate and then you left.

299
00:34:40,027 --> 00:34:42,349
It was a week on how to attain Nibbāna.

300
00:34:42,409 --> 00:34:50,079
He entered the course thinking, you know, he'd have a go and at the end he'd know Nibbāna and that was it.

301
00:34:50,139 --> 00:34:50,800
That's what he'd come for.

302
00:34:51,721 --> 00:35:00,811
Well, of course, as the course began to end, the despair entered into the heart and it took him a while to realize that it wasn't that sort of course.

303
00:35:00,831 --> 00:35:06,358
And that's why you don't get certificates after meditation courses.

304
00:35:06,418 --> 00:35:07,840
Nobody hands you a certificate.

305
00:35:09,878 --> 00:35:11,659
So this expectation.

306
00:35:12,380 --> 00:35:13,722
So here's the Buddha, you see.

307
00:35:13,782 --> 00:35:20,989
He says, I do not say that the attainment of profound knowledge comes straight away.

308
00:35:22,291 --> 00:35:31,481
Nevertheless, the attainment of profound knowledge comes by a gradual training, a gradual doing, a gradual course.

309
00:35:31,501 --> 00:35:34,103
How does the attainment of profound knowledge come?

310
00:35:34,184 --> 00:35:38,248
By means of gradual training, gradual doing and gradual course.

311
00:35:39,443 --> 00:35:42,586
As it is, one who has faith draws near.

312
00:35:43,347 --> 00:35:46,152
Drawing close, they sit down nearby.

313
00:35:46,512 --> 00:35:48,255
Sitting nearby, they lend an ear.

314
00:35:48,896 --> 00:35:50,858
Lending an ear, they hear the Dharma.

315
00:35:51,239 --> 00:35:52,862
Having heard the Dharma, they remember it.

316
00:35:53,543 --> 00:35:58,528
They test the meaning of things they have borne in mind.

317
00:35:59,530 --> 00:36:06,159
Whilst testing the meaning, things are approved of.

318
00:36:06,967 --> 00:36:08,449
They're being approved of things.

319
00:36:08,628 --> 00:36:09,891
Desire is born.

320
00:36:10,431 --> 00:36:12,775
When desire is born, they make an effort.

321
00:36:13,416 --> 00:36:15,920
Having made the effort, they weigh it up.

322
00:36:16,260 --> 00:36:18,003
Having weighed it up, they strive.

323
00:36:18,804 --> 00:36:23,710
Being self-revolute, they realize for themselves the highest truth itself.

324
00:36:24,831 --> 00:36:26,635
Penetrating by means of wisdom.

325
00:36:27,976 --> 00:36:28,056
See?

326
00:36:28,077 --> 00:36:28,737
Stages.

327
00:36:33,038 --> 00:36:40,612
And you also have to be careful that, so the whole point is that when we practice to abandon all expectation.

328
00:36:41,054 --> 00:36:41,875
This is the point you see.

329
00:36:42,295 --> 00:36:44,018
So abandon all expectation.

330
00:36:45,402 --> 00:36:51,012
And this will, if you don't, if you don't you see, then you'll get into that failure success.

331
00:36:53,018 --> 00:36:54,340
And that's where the trouble starts.

332
00:36:55,402 --> 00:37:02,936
And when you get a lack of success, it can be a sort of misunderstanding really.

333
00:37:03,757 --> 00:37:11,010
Remember that all spiritual traditions warn us that the spiritual path is full of deserts.

334
00:37:10,989 --> 00:37:13,012
dry places, empty places.

335
00:37:14,235 --> 00:37:26,074
And it's surprising how many people when they enter into that place just begin to slag off and disappear and then they reappear about 20 years later.

336
00:37:28,318 --> 00:37:37,351
But those periods when you think you are not advancing are more important than those periods when you think you are.

337
00:37:37,585 --> 00:37:40,710
That's the slog, that's the dryness, that's the desert.

338
00:37:40,730 --> 00:37:43,574
You've just got to keep one foot in front of the other.

339
00:37:44,717 --> 00:37:46,940
And I use the image before the mountain.

340
00:37:47,541 --> 00:37:55,253
So mountains are used often in the spiritual literature because they're so close to the experience of the spiritual life.

341
00:37:56,155 --> 00:38:00,382
The idea of having this constant...

342
00:38:00,402 --> 00:38:03,626
The actual practice is extremely simple.

343
00:38:03,860 --> 00:38:10,646
To climb a mountain, all you've got to remember is you put one foot in front of the other and, generally speaking, go up.

344
00:38:11,452 --> 00:38:12,173
That's it, isn't it?

345
00:38:12,815 --> 00:38:16,298
I mean, you know, you don't need any more instructions than that.

346
00:38:17,380 --> 00:38:22,806
Then, of course, there comes all sorts of techniques and ways of handling certain situations.

347
00:38:23,327 --> 00:38:25,309
Stamina, commitment, yeah?

348
00:38:25,889 --> 00:38:35,402
And the worst thing you can do on a mountain, especially the high you get, is to sit down and have a break which is just a wee bit too long and you start getting cold.

349
00:38:35,382 --> 00:38:36,983
And you drink your last cup of tea.

350
00:38:37,865 --> 00:38:38,367
And that's it.

351
00:38:38,407 --> 00:38:39,347
You're on the way down then.

352
00:38:39,768 --> 00:38:49,963
So it's a case of that commitment, especially during those periods where you feel that nothing is happening.

353
00:38:50,425 --> 00:38:52,427
It doesn't matter how long nothing is happening.

354
00:38:52,708 --> 00:38:53,650
You just keep going.

355
00:38:53,971 --> 00:38:54,530
Just keep going.

356
00:38:55,092 --> 00:38:57,576
And it's a testing time.

357
00:38:57,556 --> 00:39:06,266
You're just looking at the fact of the loss of self-esteem, the feeling that you're not going anywhere, as if there was anywhere to go, a lack of success.

358
00:39:06,947 --> 00:39:09,632
All comes up, you see, and it's the ego, you see.

359
00:39:10,092 --> 00:39:16,940
So the dryness, the aridity of practice, is one of the most potential parts to get rid of the ego.

360
00:39:17,621 --> 00:39:26,853
And, you know, usually it's a time when we give up, which is a sorrow, because it takes a bit to get up there.

361
00:39:26,918 --> 00:39:31,106
So don't worry about lack of success, just keep doing the job.

362
00:39:34,735 --> 00:39:39,105
Then of course there are the more obvious things, you know, doubt in the Buddha,

363
00:39:41,650 --> 00:39:48,844
The doubt, you see, a doubt in the Buddha always has felt to me, in a sense, slightly unnecessary.

364
00:39:49,626 --> 00:39:53,552
Because as you go along, there are side posts there.

365
00:39:53,693 --> 00:39:55,336
You don't have to believe in Nibbana.

366
00:39:55,356 --> 00:39:58,021
You don't have to believe at all in any of that stuff.

367
00:39:58,170 --> 00:40:01,016
The whole point about the Dharma is that it's immediate.

368
00:40:01,295 --> 00:40:03,119
You either benefit from it now or you don't.

369
00:40:04,320 --> 00:40:05,543
That's the point.

370
00:40:06,063 --> 00:40:24,313
But when we're practicing we might not see, shall we say, an immediate benefit from it right here and now in this present moment, but when we look back on our practice over a period of years we can see that it's helped us to progress and it's part of our progression and it might even be the fundamental reason for our progression.

371
00:40:24,293 --> 00:40:41,389
So it's that ability to see that the doubt that we have in the practice is undermined by not looking too far ahead.

372
00:40:44,353 --> 00:40:45,554
It's right here and now.

373
00:40:45,673 --> 00:40:50,958
So if we can look back and think a little bit, oh, this is a benefit, then we don't lose that sense of

374
00:40:52,981 --> 00:40:54,382
of faith in what we're doing.

375
00:40:56,023 --> 00:41:07,514
When it comes to the Sangha, that's really an extension of faith in the Buddha because the Sangha is simply other people who've said that they've actually attained the same thing.

376
00:41:09,157 --> 00:41:12,400
And the more people who say that, the more of course it gives other people confidence.

377
00:41:13,722 --> 00:41:18,246
Now these three things have to be, or at least two of them, have to be internal.

378
00:41:20,132 --> 00:41:47,507
see even at the end I've just got here even at the end you see when the Buddha actually becomes enlightened as that doubt appears is this it or is there more and that's when Mara attacks him with all the armies that's how it's put in the mythology and the Buddha touches the earth you've seen the posture the Bhoomispasa posture where he's touching the earth and that was the point where he touched the earth as a witness as it were that he had attained the end of suffering

379
00:41:48,702 --> 00:41:59,067
And the earth quaked and the earth goddess rose, wringing from her hair the water poured as libation to her by the Buddha in previous lives.

380
00:41:59,086 --> 00:42:00,130
That's nice, isn't it?

381
00:42:07,922 --> 00:42:22,737
But when we actually take the refuge, it's not simply in that historical Buddha, it's the presumption that there's a Buddha within us, that there's something within us which is to be liberated.

382
00:42:23,297 --> 00:42:26,139
And that's what you're taking your faith in.

383
00:42:26,880 --> 00:42:35,449
So when the Buddha is dying, Ananda wants to know who's going to take his place.

384
00:42:36,425 --> 00:42:41,452
Because Ananda has this overflowing faith in the Buddha.

385
00:42:42,793 --> 00:42:55,750
And the Buddha's answer is that he mustn't take faith in him as a person, but take faith in the Dharma, the teaching itself, the practice itself.

386
00:42:55,898 --> 00:43:15,628
and in himself be a light unto yourself take the Dharma as your light take the Dharma as your guide take the Dharma as your teacher take yourself as your guide yourself as your teacher so eventually this is our journey that's all the Buddha is saying and the usual quote is the Buddha's only point the way

387
00:43:15,608 --> 00:43:44,670
so eventually when we take these when we take these refuges when we make that commitment it's always a commitment to ourselves and there was only one period in Buddhist history that I know of where there was a collapse of where there was a doubt that there were some human beings who couldn't make it and it's a heresy of course

388
00:43:45,005 --> 00:43:50,114
And these people who couldn't make it were labeled the Ichikantas.

389
00:43:51,896 --> 00:43:57,706
And Ichikanta means forever going on in the world of samsara.

390
00:43:58,086 --> 00:44:01,612
There was no ending to their rebirth because they were so stupid.

391
00:44:03,262 --> 00:44:04,744
But luckily that didn't take on.

392
00:44:06,507 --> 00:44:10,534
It remains there as one of these little side schools that believe that.

393
00:44:10,594 --> 00:44:12,217
Some young beings were really thick.

394
00:44:14,081 --> 00:44:16,224
They couldn't make it, even if they tried.

395
00:44:16,244 --> 00:44:24,798
I must tell you, in Sri Lanka it's very strange to us.

396
00:44:27,192 --> 00:44:46,581
But they can tell by the shape of somebody's head, or some monks can tell, and nuns I presume, can tell by the shape of somebody's head whether they're going to make it or not.

397
00:44:47,043 --> 00:44:54,094
And the teacher at my own monastery, who was an excellent teacher, a direct disciple of the Maharshi,

398
00:44:55,340 --> 00:45:05,898
very strict, very demanding, and often wouldn't take on students, but he wouldn't take on certain students whose head wasn't quite right.

399
00:45:11,527 --> 00:45:12,148
I say no more.

400
00:45:14,592 --> 00:45:20,081
Maybe there are ways of telling things that we're not privy to, that's all there is to it.

401
00:45:29,173 --> 00:45:35,641
So I think I've just about covered all the bits that I wanted to cover.

402
00:45:36,061 --> 00:45:41,148
I suppose one thing I might just say is how to make faith grow.

403
00:45:41,188 --> 00:45:42,989
We haven't done that really.

404
00:45:43,771 --> 00:45:47,954
So first of all, there's the spiritual friendship.

405
00:45:47,974 --> 00:45:51,199
That's very important, to be with the right people.

406
00:45:51,179 --> 00:46:14,503
you undermine you know to be to be with people of like mind who are supporting you is obviously I mean the Buddha the Buddha you know Ananda says to the Buddha I believe that right relationship good relationship is only half of the spiritual livelihood and the Buddha says oh no he says it's the whole of spiritual livelihood you see

407
00:46:18,702 --> 00:46:29,742
When a meditator has a good friend, a good companion, a good comrade, it is to be expected that they will develop and cultivate the Eightfold Noble Path.

408
00:46:34,362 --> 00:46:36,746
Also to be clear about one's training.

409
00:46:37,226 --> 00:46:42,315
See, if you're sloppy with your virtue, then it also slips.

410
00:46:42,355 --> 00:46:47,382
It undermines your commitment to the path because you cannot separate insight from virtue.

411
00:46:48,164 --> 00:46:51,027
You can't have a Buddha who goes around robbing.

412
00:46:54,112 --> 00:47:00,402
Wisdom is also an act, when it expresses itself, is virtuous.

413
00:47:03,353 --> 00:47:05,938
You have to be careful of your speech especially, it says.

414
00:47:08,344 --> 00:47:11,652
You must be energetic in abandoning what is unprofitable.

415
00:47:12,653 --> 00:47:16,963
Remember that every time you attend to something, there's an act of intention.

416
00:47:17,204 --> 00:47:18,447
Therefore, it's conditioning.

417
00:47:19,088 --> 00:47:21,614
You have to be careful what programs you watch on the telly.

418
00:47:23,755 --> 00:47:26,539
And finally, the understanding of impermanence.

419
00:47:26,719 --> 00:47:31,847
The more we understand impermanence, the more we get what's known as Samvega, that enthusiasm.

420
00:47:32,226 --> 00:47:37,273
I mean, we haven't got that long, have we?

421
00:47:37,293 --> 00:47:42,641
And visits to the teacher or to a center where you get teaching.

422
00:47:43,987 --> 00:47:50,916
And also, just as an aside, the group, the evening group, your local group.

423
00:47:50,936 --> 00:47:53,179
That's always a nice fillip.

424
00:47:53,418 --> 00:48:02,188
I always remember making that effort every week to go across town in order to join a group had an effect of raising the effort for the whole practice for the week.

425
00:48:02,849 --> 00:48:06,253
And if I missed it, I could feel the lack of energy during the week.

426
00:48:06,813 --> 00:48:13,422
So remember that the effort you put into a practice is an attitude and the attitude stays with you.

427
00:48:21,856 --> 00:48:25,139
So I think that sort of brings me to an end of my little homily.

428
00:48:28,001 --> 00:48:32,646
I'll just leave you with a little final refrain taken from the Sathya Nipata.

429
00:48:34,047 --> 00:48:39,233
Faith, in the way that we've been describing it, is the best wealth to a person of this world.

430
00:48:39,773 --> 00:48:42,436
Well-practiced Dharma brings the most happiness.

431
00:48:42,737 --> 00:48:48,402
Truth is the sweetest of all tastes, and living with wisdom is said to be of the noblest kind.
